04211nam a22006735i 9780271031859DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212004pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710318597 a10.1515/97802710318592doi  a(DE-B1597)584514  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBH181b.H75 2004eb 7aPHI0010002bisacsh04a111/.852221 aHuhn, Tom, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aImitation and Society :bThe Persistence of Mimesis in the Aesthetics of Burke, Hogarth, and Kant /cTom Huhn. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2004  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b2 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLiterature and Philosophy00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 Burke and the Ambitions of Taste -- t2 Hogarth and the Lineage of Taste -- t3 Kant and the Pleasures of Taste -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book reconsiders the fate of the doctrine of mimesis in the eighteenth century. Standard accounts of the aesthetic theories of this era hold that the idea of mimesis was supplanted by the far more robust and compelling doctrines of taste and aesthetic judgment. Since the idea of mimesis was taken to apply only in the relation of art to nature, it was judged to be too limited when the focus of aesthetics changed to questions about the constitution of individual subjects in regard to taste. Tom Huhn argues that mimesis, rather than disappearing, instead became a far more pervasive idea in the eighteenth century by becoming submerged within the dynamics of the emerging accounts of judgment and taste. Mimesis also thereby became enmeshed in the ideas of sociality contained, often only implicitly, within the new accounts of aesthetic judgment. The book proceeds by reading three of the foundational treatises in aesthetics-Burke's Philosophical Enquiry into the Origin of Our Ideas of the Sublime and Beautiful, Hogarth's Analysis of Beauty, and Kant's Critique of Judgment-with an eye for discerning where arguments and analyses betray mimetic structures. Huhn attempts to explicate these books anew by arguing that they are pervaded by a mimetic dynamic. Overall, he seeks to provoke a reconsideration of eighteenth-century aesthetics that centers on its continuity with traditional notions of mimesis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAestheticsxSocial aspectsxHistoryy18th century. 0aJudgment (Aesthetics)xSocial aspectsxHistoryy18th century. 0aMimesis in artxHistory. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Aesthetics.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271031859zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271031859423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271031859.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK